{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Think of the immune system as your body's security network: a distributed team of cells, tissues and molecules that patrol, detect trouble and restore order whenever something harmful appears.",
      "title": "A bodyguard for your body"
    },
    {
      "text": "Skin, mucus, stomach acid and tears are the walls, gates and moats. They block or wash away many invaders before the internal team even needs to act—like a city’s outer defenses.",
      "title": "First line: barriers & patrols"
    },
    {
      "text": "Innate immunity is the fast, generalist response. Cells like macrophages and neutrophils rush in, eat or neutralize invaders, and trigger inflammation—like first responders arriving on scene.",
      "title": "Innate immunity: rapid response"
    },
    {
      "text": "Adaptive immunity is slower but precise. B cells build custom antibodies and T cells target infected cells. It’s like tailoring weapons and strategies for a specific criminal once you’ve identified them.",
      "title": "Adaptive immunity: tailor-made defense"
    },
    {
      "text": "Who does what? Macrophages eat intruders, neutrophils swarm, natural killer cells destroy abnormal cells, helper T cells coordinate, cytotoxic T cells kill infected cells, B cells make antibodies.",
      "title": "Who's on the team?"
    },
    {
      "text": "These parts cooperate: innate sensors raise the alarm and present clues to adaptive cells, which then produce specific antibodies or killer cells. Imagine firefighters calling detectives to investigate and act.",
      "title": "Teamwork: how parts coordinate"
    },
    {
      "text": "Recognition works like fingerprinting: some defenses spot common patterns, others learn exact molecular 'fingerprints.' The system usually ignores self; when it fails, you get autoimmunity or allergies.",
      "title": "How the body recognizes threats"
    },
    {
      "text": "Common mix-ups: inflammation is a response, not always an infection; antibodies tag invaders but don’t do all the killing; allergies are overreactions, and immune strength can vary by condition.",
      "title": "Common confusions cleared up"
    },
    {
      "text": "Why it matters: understanding these layers helps explain symptoms (redness, swelling, fever), tests, and why some treatments work. It gives you a mental map of how health is defended and restored.",
      "title": "Why understanding it matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Photosynthesis is how plants, algae and some bacteria turn sunlight into chemical energy. In simple terms: light energy → stored energy in sugars. Think of it as sunlight being captured and bottled as food for the organism.",
      "title": "Photosynthesis in plain terms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Chloroplasts are the mini factories where photosynthesis happens. Inside are stacked thylakoid membranes (solar panels) and the stroma (workroom) where different steps are carried out.",
      "title": "The chloroplast: the solar factory"
    },
    {
      "text": "Light reactions are the charging stage. Pigments like chlorophyll grab photons, split water, and push electrons through a chain to make ATP and NADPH—like charging batteries—and release O₂ as a byproduct.",
      "title": "Light reactions: charging the batteries"
    },
    {
      "text": "The Calvin cycle (carbon fixation) is the sugar-making kitchen. Using ATP and NADPH, the plant converts CO₂ into simple sugars. Think of it as baking bread using stored energy and basic ingredients.",
      "title": "Calvin cycle: baking sugar"
    },
    {
      "text": "How the parts connect: light reactions make ATP/NADPH; those fuel the Calvin cycle to fix CO₂ into sugar. Energy flows from sunlight to chemical bonds; oxygen leaves as a useful waste product.",
      "title": "How the parts connect"
    },
    {
      "text": "You recognize photosynthesis in green leaves, algae mats, and even the tiny phytoplankton in oceans that turn sunlight into food. In ponds you can see oxygen bubbles—tiny evidence of the process.",
      "title": "Where you spot photosynthesis"
    },
    {
      "text": "Common confusions: photosynthesis makes sugars and O₂, while cellular respiration uses sugars for energy—both happen in plants. ‘Dark reactions’ need light-created energy, so they aren’t truly dark.",
      "title": "Common confusions cleared up"
    },
    {
      "text": "Why it matters: photosynthesis powers food webs, supplies atmospheric oxygen, and stores carbon as biomass. Understanding it helps with agriculture, ecosystems, and tackling climate challenges.",
      "title": "Why understanding it matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "At its simplest, CRISPR-Cas9 is a programmable molecular tool that finds a specific DNA sequence and makes a precise cut. Think of it like a find-and-cut command in a text editor for the genome.",
      "title": "CRISPR-Cas9 in one line"
    },
    {
      "text": "Guide RNA (gRNA) is the address label. A short RNA sequence matches the target DNA like a postal code and steers Cas9 to the right spot. Without the right address, the cutter won't go where you want.",
      "title": "Guide RNA: the GPS"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cas9 is the molecular scissors. Once guided to the spot, Cas9 binds the DNA and makes a double-strand cut. Imagine a pair of scissors that only opens when it’s handed the right map.",
      "title": "Cas9: the molecular scissors"
    },
    {
      "text": "PAM is the tiny landing pad next to the target DNA. Cas9 needs this short DNA motif to bind—think of PAM as a lock that must be present before the scissors can unlock and cut.",
      "title": "PAM: the unlocking code"
    },
    {
      "text": "Targeting works by base-pair matching: the gRNA pairs with one DNA strand, forming an R-loop that lets Cas9 check the sequence and then cleave both strands at a precise spot.",
      "title": "How binding and cutting happen"
    },
    {
      "text": "After the cut, the cell's repair machinery takes over. NHEJ is fast and messy—often inserting or deleting bases. HDR is slower but precise, using a template to rewrite the sequence.",
      "title": "Cell repair: NHEJ vs HDR"
    },
    {
      "text": "Different edits come from how the cell repairs the break. NHEJ can knock out a gene (disrupt it); HDR can swap in a new sequence. Think of NHEJ as patching and HDR as replacing a tile.",
      "title": "Editing outcomes: disrupt or replace"
    },
    {
      "text": "Common confusions: CRISPR is the tool, not the therapy; Cas9 is guided by RNA not DNA; cuts don’t equal intended edits—the cell’s repair determines the final change.",
      "title": "Common misunderstandings"
    },
    {
      "text": "You can spot CRISPR results by sequencing: short insertions or deletions at the cut site, or precise sequence changes if a template was used. Like seeing edits in a document’s revision history.",
      "title": "How to recognize CRISPR edits"
    },
    {
      "text": "Why it matters: knowing the parts and repair paths helps predict outcomes, risks, and limitations. Understanding the mechanism is the first step toward safe and sensible applications.",
      "title": "Why understanding CRISPR helps"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Neurotransmissão é a forma como neurônios trocam mensagens: um pulso elétrico vira uma mensagem química que atravessa uma pequena lacuna para influenciar outro neurônio.",
      "title": "A ideia central"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pense no neurônio como um carteiro: dendritos recebem cartas, o corpo processa e o axônio leva a mensagem até terminais prontos para enviar.",
      "title": "Neurônio: remetente e receptor"
    },
    {
      "text": "O potencial de ação é o pulso elétrico que corre pelo axônio — como uma fileira de dominós elétrica. É rápido e funciona no estilo “tudo ou nada”.",
      "title": "Potencial de ação: o pulso elétrico"
    },
    {
      "text": "A sinapse é a estação onde a troca acontece: uma pequena lacuna entre terminais do emissor e a membrana do receptor — eles não chegam a se tocar.",
      "title": "Sinapse: a estação de transferência"
    },
    {
      "text": "Neurotransmissores são as “cartas” químicas armazenadas em vesículas. Quando chegam, as vesículas se abrem e liberam as mensagens na sinapse.",
      "title": "Neurotransmissores: as mensagens químicas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Receptores na célula receptora são como fechaduras: cada neurotransmissor é uma chave. Só quando a chave encaixa surge uma resposta específica.",
      "title": "Receptores: fechadura e chave"
    },
    {
      "text": "Depois do envio a mensagem precisa acabar: enzimas quebram neurotransmissores ou transportadores os recolhem para reciclagem — como limpar a bancada após cozinhar.",
      "title": "Depois do envio: limpeza e reciclagem"
    },
    {
      "text": "A ligação pode excitar ou inibir: algumas mensagens aumentam a chance de disparo (volume pra cima), outras diminuem (volume pra baixo).",
      "title": "Efeitos na célula receptora"
    },
    {
      "text": "Confusões comuns: neurotransmissores não são hormônios, sinapses não são contato físico e sinais elétricos e químicos trabalham juntos, não separados.",
      "title": "Confusões comuns"
    },
    {
      "text": "Saber isso ajuda a conectar como comportamentos, emoções e drogas atuam no cérebro — é o mapa básico para entender movimento, humor e aprendizagem.",
      "title": "Por que isso importa?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Un mecanismo de consenso es el conjunto de reglas e incentivos que permiten a los participantes acordar cuál es el estado único del libro de cuentas compartido. Piensa en ello como reglas para decidir qué páginas se pegan en el cuaderno común.",
      "title": "La idea central del consenso"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las piezas esenciales: nodos (participantes), transacciones, mempool (cola de transacciones), bloques, cadena (blockchain), validadores/mineros y criptografía (firmas y hashes). Son como instrumentos en una orquesta que siguen una partitura común.",
      "title": "Piezas esenciales"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cómo encajan: los nodos propagan transacciones, algunos proponen bloques y el resto los verifica contra reglas comunes. Si la mayoría acepta un bloque, se añade a la cadena. Imagina pasar recetas y que la comunidad las firme antes de cocinar.",
      "title": "Cómo se conectan las piezas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Proof of Work (PoW) es una forma de elegir quién propone bloques: los mineros compiten resolviendo un rompecabezas criptográfico (buscar un nonce que produzca un hash válido). Piensa en una lotería costosa: solo quien gana añade la página al cuaderno.",
      "title": "Qué es Proof of Work (PoW)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Validación de transacciones: una firma prueba que eres el dueño; el nodo comprueba saldos (modelo UTXO o cuentas) y que no haya doble gasto. Las transacciones válidas esperan en el mempool hasta que un bloque las incluye.",
      "title": "Cómo se validan las transacciones"
    },
    {
      "text": "Confirmaciones y bifurcaciones: cada bloque añadido es una confirmación; cuantas más confirmaciones, más confianza. A veces surgen dos bloques a la vez (bifurcación) y la cadena con más trabajo gana. Es como pegar páginas: cuanto más pegadas, menos probable que se despeguen.",
      "title": "Confirmaciones y bifurcaciones"
    },
    {
      "text": "Confusiones comunes: consenso no significa que todos estén de acuerdo al instante; PoW no valida el contenido, solo evita que crear bloques sea barato; y la seguridad puede verse afectada por concentración de mineros (riesgo 51%).",
      "title": "Malos entendidos comunes"
    },
    {
      "text": "¿Y por qué importa? Entender esto te ayuda a evaluar trade‑offs: seguridad vs energía, velocidad vs descentralización. Como elegir un coche: sabes qué sacrificar según el uso que le darás.",
      "title": "Por qué importa entenderlo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A compiler is a translator that turns human-friendly source code into machine-friendly instructions. Imagine a multilingual translator converting a book into a film script the machine can act on.",
      "title": "What a Compiler Is"
    },
    {
      "text": "Think of source code as a recipe and the executable as the finished dish. The compiler reads the recipe, checks it makes sense, then produces step-by-step instructions a kitchen (CPU) can follow.",
      "title": "From Recipe to Ready Meal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Compilers work as a pipeline: each phase refines the program representation, passing a clearer, more detailed form to the next stage—like an assembly line polishing a product.",
      "title": "The Pipeline Idea"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lexical analysis chops raw text into tokens—words and symbols. Imagine turning a paragraph into a list of ingredients and quantities before you try to cook.",
      "title": "Finding the Building Blocks"
    },
    {
      "text": "Parsing arranges tokens into structure: the program's grammar tree. Think of it as building the recipe's ordered steps so you can see which actions depend on others.",
      "title": "Building the Structure"
    },
    {
      "text": "Semantic analysis checks meaning and consistency: types, variable scopes, and rules. It's like proofreading a recipe to ensure oven temperatures and ingredient amounts make sense.",
      "title": "Checking the Meaning"
    },
    {
      "text": "The compiler converts code into an intermediate representation (IR)—a neutral blueprint. Imagine rewriting recipes into a standard format the whole kitchen team understands.",
      "title": "A Common Internal Language"
    },
    {
      "text": "Optimizations rewrite the IR to run faster or use less memory. Think of them as tuning a car engine or trimming a recipe to be quicker without changing the meal's taste.",
      "title": "Making It Faster and Smaller"
    },
    {
      "text": "Code generation maps the optimized blueprint to actual machine instructions for a specific CPU—like translating a universal recipe into the exact steps for a particular stove.",
      "title": "Turning Blueprints into Instructions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Linking and loading stitch modules and libraries into one executable and place it into memory to run—like assembling parts of a meal and plating them for service.",
      "title": "Assembling the Final Program"
    },
    {
      "text": "You meet compilers as tools like gcc/clang, javac, rustc, or as transpilers (Babel) that convert between high-level languages. They live in build tools and IDEs quietly doing their work.",
      "title": "Where You See Compilers"
    },
    {
      "text": "Common confusion: compilers translate ahead of time; interpreters execute code directly; assemblers translate assembly to machine code. Think translator vs live actor vs local dialect converter.",
      "title": "Compiler vs Interpreter vs Assembler"
    },
    {
      "text": "Why this view matters: seeing a compiler as analyzer + transformer helps you reason about errors, performance, and language features. It's a mental map for debugging and design choices.",
      "title": "Why Understanding Compilers Helps"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A neural network learns by adjusting numeric connections (weights) so its outputs match examples. Think of it like tuning radio knobs: each tiny tweak makes the signal (prediction) clearer over many tries.",
      "title": "Learning as guided adjustment"
    },
    {
      "text": "A forward pass is when input flows through layers and the network produces a prediction. Imagine an assembly line: each station transforms the part a bit until a final product (the prediction) comes out.",
      "title": "Predicting: the forward pass"
    },
    {
      "text": "The loss is a single number that measures how far the prediction is from the target. Think of it as a scorecard or the distance on a map—the network's job is to make that number smaller.",
      "title": "How mistakes are measured"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gradients tell you which direction to change each weight to reduce loss. Think of standing on a hill: the gradient points steepest uphill, so you move the opposite way to descend toward lower loss.",
      "title": "Which way to change: gradients"
    },
    {
      "text": "Backpropagation is the systematic recipe that computes gradients across layers using the chain rule. Imagine passing feedback down a relay: each layer receives guidance about how to adjust based on later layers.",
      "title": "How feedback reaches every layer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Updating weights means nudging each connection opposite the gradient so the loss shrinks. These are small, repeated corrections—like steering a ship with gentle turns rather than sudden, large yanks.",
      "title": "Small nudges: weight updates"
    },
    {
      "text": "The learning rate and optimizer control step size and pattern. Learning rate is the accelerator pedal; optimizers (momentum, Adam) add memory or scale steps so updates are steadier and faster.",
      "title": "Steering: learning rate and optimizers"
    },
    {
      "text": "Common confusions: gradients are directions, not raw 'errors'; too-large steps overshoot; deep nets can suffer vanishing or exploding gradients. Think volume control—too low you miss detail, too high you distort.",
      "title": "Common confusions to watch"
    },
    {
      "text": "You see this learning loop in real systems: image classifiers improving after training, voice assistants refining transcriptions, or a recommender adapting to clicks—each update nudges behavior toward better results.",
      "title": "Where you see this in practice"
    },
    {
      "text": "Understanding these parts helps you predict and debug model behavior—if training stalls, you check loss, gradients, or step size instead of guessing. It's like knowing how an engine responds to different pedals.",
      "title": "Why this understanding matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Política monetária são as ações do banco central para regular a quantidade de dinheiro e o custo do crédito, buscando preços estáveis e emprego. Pense nisso como um termostato que ajusta a “temperatura” da economia.",
      "title": "O que é política monetária"
    },
    {
      "text": "As principais ferramentas são: taxa básica de juros (o preço do dinheiro), operações de mercado aberto (comprar/vender títulos), reservas obrigatórias, facilidades de liquidez e, em crises, compra de ativos (QE). Cada uma altera crédito ou liquidez.",
      "title": "Ferramentas principais"
    },
    {
      "text": "A taxa básica é como o compasso de uma música: quando sobe, outras taxas seguem o ritmo e o crédito fica mais caro; quando cai, empréstimos e consumo tendem a aumentar. É o sinal mais direto que o banco central envia.",
      "title": "A taxa de juros como sinal"
    },
    {
      "text": "As ferramentas atingem a economia por canais: taxa de juros (custo do crédito), canal do crédito (bancos emprestam mais ou menos), câmbio (impacta exportações/importações), preços de ativos e expectativas. Imagine ondas num lago: uma pedra causa várias ondulações.",
      "title": "Como a política alcança a economia"
    },
    {
      "text": "Expectativas importam muito: promessas do banco central e sua credibilidade moldam decisões hoje. Pense num técnico que diz que vai mudar a tática — o time já se ajusta antes do apito final.",
      "title": "O papel das expectativas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Efeitos têm prazos: alguns aparecem rápido (mercados, câmbio), outros levam meses ou anos (investimento, emprego). É como virar um navio grande: demora para a direção mudar totalmente.",
      "title": "Efeitos e prazos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Como reconhecer? Veja a taxa básica anunciada, comunicados e projeções do banco central, movimentos nos juros de mercado, câmbio, crédito bancário e inflação. Notícias sobre decisões e atas explicam os sinais.",
      "title": "Onde você percebe a política"
    },
    {
      "text": "Confusões comuns: política monetária não é o mesmo que política fiscal (gastos e impostos); não funciona como interruptor instantâneo; e independência do banco central afeta credibilidade — não é mágica.",
      "title": "Erros que as pessoas cometem"
    },
    {
      "text": "Por que isso importa? Entender política monetária ajuda a interpretar inflação, taxas de empréstimo, rendimento de investimentos e o mercado de trabalho — e a tomar decisões financeiras mais informadas.",
      "title": "Por que entender isso importa"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A vaccine is a safe rehearsal for your immune system. It shows harmless pieces or instructions of a germ so your body learns to spot and respond fast — like a fire drill that prepares people for a real emergency.",
      "title": "Vaccines as immune training"
    },
    {
      "text": "An antigen is the part of a germ the immune system recognizes. Think of it like a wanted poster: vaccines show a clear picture so your defenses can recognize the real intruder later.",
      "title": "Antigens: the immune's 'wanted poster'"
    },
    {
      "text": "B cells are antibody factories. When they see the antigen they produce antibodies — like guided missiles that stick to a virus and stop it from entering cells or mark it for cleanup.",
      "title": "Antibodies and B cells"
    },
    {
      "text": "T cells are the team's coordinators and cleaners. Helper T cells give instructions; killer T cells destroy infected cells. Together they organize a precise, targeted response.",
      "title": "T cells: coordinators & cleaners"
    },
    {
      "text": "Some B and T cells become memory cells — a long-term file of the invader. On re-exposure they react faster and stronger, turning a potential crisis into a brief, mild encounter.",
      "title": "Memory cells: the long-term file"
    },
    {
      "text": "Vaccines are different training tools: live weakened germs (dress rehearsal), killed germs (mannequin), pieces of a germ (uniform patch), toxoids (neutralized toxin), mRNA (blueprint), viral vectors (delivery truck).",
      "title": "Vaccine types: different training tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Adjuvants are like coaches added to some vaccines. They nudge the immune system to pay more attention so you get a stronger, longer-lasting memory from the same antigen.",
      "title": "Adjuvants: the immune coach"
    },
    {
      "text": "Immunity develops in stages: a slower primary response after the first dose, then memory forms. Boosters are reminders that sharpen and extend protection — not instant shields, but long-term defense.",
      "title": "How immunity builds over time"
    },
    {
      "text": "You see vaccine protection as fewer infections, milder illness if infected, and fewer outbreaks in the community. Think of it like a neighborhood watch that lowers crime for everyone.",
      "title": "Signs a vaccine is working"
    },
    {
      "text": "Common confusions: most vaccines can't cause the disease; rare live vaccines may cause mild symptoms in vulnerable people. Vaccines don't 'overload' your immune system. Side effects are usually short-lived signals your body is learning.",
      "title": "Common confusions clarified"
    },
    {
      "text": "Understanding how vaccines work helps you make informed choices, appreciate timing (like boosters), and see how individual protection adds up to community safety — it's practical, not just theoretical.",
      "title": "Why understanding matters"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Piensa en una receta que siempre da el mismo pastel: una función hash criptográfica es una regla matemática que toma cualquier dato y devuelve un resumen de tamaño fijo. Es la forma compacta y consistente de representar información larga.",
      "title": "La idea central"
    },
    {
      "text": "Entrada larga, salida corta: puedes darle un libro o una foto; siempre produce un valor final con longitud fija. Es como poner ingredientes diferentes en un molde idéntico: sale algo con la misma forma.",
      "title": "Entrada, proceso y salida"
    },
    {
      "text": "Determinista y rápida: la misma entrada siempre produce la misma salida, y calcularla es eficiente. Imagina una fotocopiadora rápida: siempre te da la misma copia si le pones el mismo original.",
      "title": "Predecible y eficiente"
    },
    {
      "text": "Unidireccionalidad: invertir el resumen para recuperar la entrada es impráctico. Piensa en hornear un pastel: difícil saber exactamente la receta original mirando solo el pastel.",
      "title": "No reversible (one‑way)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Resistencia a colisiones: encontrar dos entradas distintas que produzcan el mismo resumen debe ser extremadamente difícil. Es como buscar dos llaves diferentes que abran la misma cerradura por casualidad.",
      "title": "Dificultad para empates"
    },
    {
      "text": "Segunda preimagen: dado un mensaje y su resumen, hallar otro mensaje con el mismo resumen debe ser inviable. Es distinto a la colisión general; aquí empiezas con una entrada concreta.",
      "title": "Protección contra copias alternativas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cómo se arma por dentro: los datos se dividen en bloques, se mezclan y se condensan mediante rondas y funciones de compresión hasta obtener el resumen final. Piensa en una línea de cocina que va transformando ingredientes paso a paso.",
      "title": "Componentes y flujo interno"
    },
    {
      "text": "Dónde las ves en la vida real: direcciones de bloques, verificación rápida en sistemas, proteger contraseñas (con técnicas extra), y detectar duplicados en almacenamiento. Son herramientas para representar y comparar datos.",
      "title": "Reconocerlas en aplicaciones"
    },
    {
      "text": "Confusiones comunes: no son cifrado ni claves secretas; no garantizan ausencia absoluta de colisiones, sólo que encontrarlas es impráctico; y el contexto importa (por ejemplo, usar sal en contraseñas).",
      "title": "Errores frecuentes y aclaraciones"
    },
    {
      "text": "Por qué importa entenderlas: saber qué propiedades ofrecen te ayuda a evaluar riesgos y elegir soluciones: no es magia, es un conjunto de garantías matemáticas con límites prácticos.",
      "title": "Por qué importa comprenderlas"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Plate tectonics is the idea that Earth's outer shell is broken into large, rigid slabs (plates) that slowly move and interact, shaping the planet's surface over millions of years.",
      "title": "Plate tectonics in one line"
    },
    {
      "text": "A tectonic plate is a chunk of the cool, strong outer shell (the lithosphere). It includes crust and the uppermost mantle — think of sturdy tiles floating on something softer beneath.",
      "title": "What's a tectonic plate?"
    },
    {
      "text": "Beneath the plates the asthenosphere is hotter and squishier. It flows very slowly, letting plates glide. Imagine heavy tiles sliding on warm, thick honey.",
      "title": "The soft layer below the plates"
    },
    {
      "text": "Plates meet at three main boundary types: pull apart (divergent), push together (convergent), or slide past (transform). Each type creates distinct behaviors and landforms.",
      "title": "The three boundary types"
    },
    {
      "text": "At divergent edges plates separate and new crust forms. Think of a zipper opening: molten rock wells up, cools, and builds ridges and rift valleys.",
      "title": "Divergent boundaries"
    },
    {
      "text": "At convergent edges one plate may dive under another (subduction) or two crumple up to form mountains. Picture one sheet sliding under a heavier one or two sheets folding together.",
      "title": "Convergent boundaries"
